**(3)** 讨论假设 (c) 的崩溃。在物理纸带上，符号的读写不是完全可靠的——热噪声、量子涨落、材料缺陷都会引入错误。假设每个格子每秒有一个极小的独立概率 p 发生"比特翻转"（被热噪声随机改写）。纸带总共有 N 个格子。整条纸带在 1 秒内至少发生一次错误的概率 P(N) 是多少？当 N → ∞ 时 P(N) → ?

这意味着什么——为什么图灵机依赖的"符号永不自行改变"是只对有限系统才成立的近似，而对无限系统必然失效？如果我们在每个格子上加入纠错码（ECC）来降低有效错误率，这是否能解决 N → ∞ 的问题？为什么能或为什么不能？

Now consider the collapse of assumption (c). On a physical tape, symbol read/write is not perfectly reliable — thermal noise, quantum fluctuations, and material defects all introduce errors. Suppose each cell has a tiny independent probability p per second of suffering a "bit flip" (being randomly rewritten by thermal noise). The tape has N total cells. What is the probability P(N) that at least one error occurs anywhere on the tape within 1 second? As N → ∞, P(N) → ?

What does this imply — why is the Turing machine's premise of "symbols never change spontaneously" an approximation that holds only for finite systems, and must fail for infinite ones? If we add error-correcting codes (ECC) to each cell to reduce the effective error rate, does this solve the N → ∞ problem? Why or why not?

*提示：P(N) = 1 − (1−p)^N。当 N → ∞ 时，即使 p 极小，P(N) → 1。这类似于第五章的逻辑——"绝对现在"在局部可以近似维持（指甲盖上的 CPU），但在全局必然崩溃（互联网）。Hint: P(N) = 1 − (1−p)^N. As N → ∞, even for vanishingly small p, P(N) → 1. This mirrors Chapter 5's logic — "absolute now" can be approximately maintained locally (a CPU on a fingernail), but must collapse globally (the internet).*

