**(5)** 图灵的"无限"是一个数学概念，不是一个工程目标。当我们尝试在物理世界中逼近这个数学概念时，物理定律先给出警告（延迟、质量、能量），然后直接拒绝（有限的原子数、必然的噪声、光速上限）。这个"先是困难、再是不可能"的过渡，和第五章的"先是昂贵、再是不现实"的尺度楼梯，是否是同一个模式？它们共同指向了物理世界的哪条根本限制？

Turing's "infinite" is a mathematical concept, not an engineering goal. When we try to approach this mathematical concept in the physical world, the laws of physics first warn us (delay, mass, energy), then outright refuse us (finite atoms, inevitable noise, speed-of-light ceiling). Is this transition from "first difficult, then impossible" the same pattern as Chapter 5's scale staircase from "first expensive, then impractical"? What fundamental limitation of the physical world do they jointly point to?

